AU  - STEIN, JEREMY
Y1  - 1989/09/01
PY  - 1989
DA  - 1989/09/01
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1111/j.1540-6261.1989.tb02635.x
T2  - The Journal of Finance
JF  - The Journal of Finance
JO  - The Journal of Finance
JA  - The Journal of Finance
SP  - 1011
EP  - 1023
VL  - 44
IS  - 4
PB  - John Wiley & Sons, Ltd
SN  - 0022-1082
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1111/j.1540-6261.1989.tb02635.x
Y2  - 2024/03/26
N2  - ABSTRACT This paper examines the ?term structure? of options' implied volatilities, using data on S&P 100 index options. Because implied volatility is strongly mean reverting, the implied volatility on a longer maturity option should move by less than one percent in response to a one percent move in the implied volatility of a shorter maturity option. Empirically, this elasticity turns out to be larger than suggested by rational expectations theory?long-maturity options tend to ?overreact? to changes in the implied volatility of short-maturity options.
ER  - 

